	abstract = {Wearable, portable, implantable, and remote healthcare has rapidly transitioned into the era of digital health, powered by Internet of things (IoT) applications that monitor, document, and track vital health indicators to save lives and treat diseases. Health management is improved with IoT devices. Biomedical gadgets are now everywhere because of IoT and connectivity technology. Industrialization has elevated patient and healthcare provider expectations. Biomedical informatics researchers may use healthcare wearables to solve complex healthcare problems and make better health choices since they have risen quickly and are projected to continue. Popular mobile healthcare technology includes implantable medical devices. The majority of wearables are for health and enjoyment. Implantable techniques cure diabetes and blood pressure. Wearables and linked healthcare studies assist chronically sick patients and others monitor their health without visiting a doctor during the COVID-19 epidemic. The objective of the work is stopping pandemics and saving users. Wearables, mobile healthcare, and sensor informatics provide numerous benefits, but real-time growth is limited. Common challenges include increased expenses, difficulties in accessing data from wearable devices, inaccuracies in treatments, concerns about security and privacy, and problems in communicating. Sensor informatics and IoT technologies, such as 5G networks and distributed machine learning, are critical before portable, implantable, and smartphone-based health monitoring. By effectively arranging and evaluating health information to improve patient health, end users experience increased convenience. Overall, this research is diverse. New IoT and sensor informatics technologies necessitate interdisciplinary vital sign and activity monitoring and emergency response. Due to advanced research, a simple, dependable, real-time healthcare integrating solution is possible. Implementing IoT and sensor inf